05362nam a22006735i 9783111063836DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831110638367 a10.1515/97831110638362doi  a(DE-B1597)638761  a(OCoLC)1415892849  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSOC0530002bisacsh1 aPastore, Rosina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVedānta, Bhakti, and Their Early Modern Sources :bPhilosophical and Religious Dimensions of Brajvāsīdās's Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka /cRosina Pastore. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XIV, 360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWelten Süd- und Zentralasiens / Worlds of South and Inner Asia / Mondes de l'Asie du Sud et de l'Asie Centrale : Im Auftrag der Schweizerischen Asiengesellschaft / On behalf of the Swiss Asia Society / Au nom de la Société Suisse-Asie ,x1661-755X ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tNote to the Reader -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Critical Study of the Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka -- t1 Brajvāsīdās's Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka -- t2 The Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka and the Prabodhacandrodaya Tradition -- t3 Tulsīdās's Rāmcaritmānas and the Prabodhacandrodaya Story -- t4 The Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka's Vedānta and Bhakti -- tConclusion -- tPart II: Annotated Translation of the Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka -- tNote to the Translation -- tSelection of Dramatis Personae -- tSelection of Additional Characters -- tACT I -- tACT II -- tACT III -- tACT IV -- tACT V -- tACT VI -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume considers the Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka (c. 1760 CE), an allegorical drama composed by Brajvāsīdās in Brajbhāṣā. It contributes to the study of vernacular nāṭakas with its first complete English translation. Moreover, the critical analysis shows that the foundational Sanskrit texts for Vedānta and those for Bhakti play a part in the Prabodhacandrodaya Nāṭaka's philosophical and religious edifice. At the same time, the investigation demonstrates that Brajvāsīdās expresses several philosophical ideas by adaptively reusing the Rāmcaritmānas by Tulsīdās (c. 1574 CE). Brajvāsīdās composes a dohā by combining one line of his invention with a line from the Mānas. This method is employed throughout all the personified metaphysical concepts. That Brajvāsī not only read Bhakti but also Vedānta through the Rāmcaritmānas highlights the philosophical and literary creativity in 18th c. North India. It points to the necessity to rethink the sources of Vedānta philosophies, by including works non-conventional for language and genre, because not in Sanskrit and not śāstras. Such sources may not be original in their contribution per se but are essential to understand how early modern philosophy was done, conceived and transmitted.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Regional Studies.2bisacsh  aBhakti.  aEarly Modern.  aVedānta.  aVernacular.2 aSchweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408